Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.99,0:00:07.60,Default,,0,0,0,,The most crucial moment in life is during decision making.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:08.95,0:00:14.05,Default,,0,0,0,,The Pacific War taught us the preciousness of peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:14.05,0:00:19.96,Default,,0,0,0,,But also instilled \Nnumerous lessons on how to live.{unsure, lit is "for the sake of living, precepts, numerous left behind"}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:24.38,0:00:31.64,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(100,700)\c&H0007DF&\fs100\b1\bord0\blur1}Animentary\N{\b\c&HE0DBF3&}Decision
Dialogue: 0,0:00:35.21,0:00:42.98,Default,,0,0,30,,Wit is your weapon{honestly no clue what is megurase here, deepl says "rack one's brain"}\NRemember to use your head{智恵をめぐらせ 頭を使え}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:42.98,0:00:50.95,Default,,0,0,30,,Repress your anguish, \NIf you are a man{悩み抜け抜け 男なら}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.95,0:00:59.24,Default,,0,0,30,,One decision is enough \NTo make others cry or laugh{泣くも笑うも 決断ひとつ}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:59.24,0:01:06.69,Default,,0,0,30,,If you win, don't hold your head high, \NIf you lose, don't cry{勝っておごるな 敗れて泣くな}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:06.69,0:01:14.55,Default,,0,0,30,,Men, don't you ever let others see your tears{男 涙は見せぬもの}
Comment: 0,0:01:34.91,0:01:34.95,Default,,0,0,0,,{ch}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:36.48,0:01:39.26,Default,,0,0,0,,July 1944.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:39.26,0:01:44.63,Default,,0,0,0,,As a result of the devastating defeat at the Battle of the Mariana Islands and the annihilation of the Saipan garrison, {gyokusai again, could go with "annihilation of the saipan garrison" here; actually the official english name is https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_the_Philippine_Sea but we clearly hear mariana there: battle off the coast of mariana}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:44.63,0:01:50.36,Default,,0,0,0,,the US forces were now \Nthe undisputed masters of the sea in the Western Pacific. {lit is "... passed to american hands entirely" but he doesn't say "from japanese hands" so it sounds kinda awkward - as though it was americans who were defeated in the mariana battle}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:51.26,0:01:58.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Then, in September of that year, the 7th Fleet, \Nunder the Supreme Allied Commander Douglas MacArthur,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:58.34,0:02:03.27,Default,,0,0,0,,rallied in Leyte Gulf, south of the Luzon Island.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:03.96,0:02:09.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Determined to meet them head-on, \Nthe Japanese Combined Fleet initiated Operation Sho Part 1 -
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.23,0:02:15.44,Default,,0,0,0,,by mustering all their remaining forces \Nand starting their advance towards the shores of Leyte
Dialogue: 0,0:02:15.44,0:02:21.68,Default,,0,0,0,,in the early hours of October 18th, 1944.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:23.52,0:02:27.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Our nation's future strength hinges on this one battle. {lit is "offense and defense" w/e that means; irl it was "the rise and fall of the imperial japan depends on this one battle" or at least this is the translation i found}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:27.20,0:02:31.94,Default,,0,0,0,,However, the enemy task force that invaded Leyte \Nnumbers over 700 vessels. {probably counting with the landing boats? no way they had that many across all N battles of leyte gulf}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:31.94,0:02:35.31,Default,,0,0,0,,As for the planes, at least 1000 \Nby the most conservative estimates. {that's closer, they had about 900 in the battle of philippine sea}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:35.31,0:02:41.41,Default,,0,0,0,,On the other hand, our 1st Air Fleet \Ncan barely field 100 operable planes.
Dialogue: 1,0:02:42.27,0:02:49.01,Default,,0,0,0,,As arranged previously, Kurita's and Nishimura's fleets \Nwill depart towards Leyte from Borneo and Brunei Bay.
